---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { APPS, SEGMENTS, USE_CASES, allPaths, description, pageTitle, siteFromHost } from '../content';
const site = siteFromHost();
const path = '';
const title = pageTitle(site, path);
const desc = description(site, path);
const recommended = APPS.filter(a => a.channels.includes(site.channel) || a.channels.includes('marketing')).slice(0,10);
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path="/">
  <section class="border-b-2 rule bg-[linear-gradient(135deg,#fbf3e4,#fff7ed_55%,#fed7aa)] py-20 md:py-28">
    <div class="container grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[1.05fr_.95fr] lg:items-center">
      <div>
        <div class="kicker">The retention newspaper for Shopify merchants</div>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-8">Best {site.primaryKeyword} for stores that want email to feel owned, useful, and measurable</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl text-stone-700">{site.heroPromise} This edition focuses only on email and lifecycle work: welcome series, abandoned cart, browse abandonment, post-purchase teaching, replenishment reminders, launch calendars, winback, VIP treatment, and the reporting discipline required to keep sending profitably.</p>
        <div class="mt-9 flex flex-wrap gap-4"><a class="btn btn-primary" href="/apps">Read app reviews</a><a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/use-cases/welcome-series">Start with welcome email</a></div>
      </div>
      <div class="paper p-7">
        <div class="badge">Editor's note</div>
        <h2 class="mt-5 text-4xl font-black text-stone-950">Email is not a blast channel. It is the store's memory.</h2>
        <p class="mt-5 text-stone-700">The best {site.keywordPlural} remember what shoppers viewed, bought, ignored, returned to, replenished, and asked for. {site.bestOverallReason} A good email platform should make those memories easy to turn into helpful messages without making every buyer feel like a row in a spreadsheet.</p>
        <div class="mt-6 grid grid-cols-3 gap-3 text-center text-sm"><div class="border-2 border-stone-900 bg-orange-100 p-3"><strong class="block text-2xl">{allPaths().length}</strong>pages</div><div class="border-2 border-stone-900 bg-orange-100 p-3"><strong class="block text-2xl">21</strong>apps</div><div class="border-2 border-stone-900 bg-orange-100 p-3"><strong class="block text-2xl">1</strong>email lens</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-16">
    <div class="mb-8 flex flex-col justify-between gap-5 md:flex-row md:items-end"><div><span class="badge">Reviewed shortlist</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Email tools to evaluate first</h2></div><a class="link" href="/apps">All app reviews</a></div>
    <div class="grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-5">{recommended.map((app, i) => <a class="card" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}><div class="text-sm font-black text-orange-800">No. {i+1} · {app.category}</div><h3 class="mt-3 text-2xl font-black text-stone-950">{app.name}</h3><p class="mt-3 text-sm text-stone-700">{app.bestFor}</p><p class="mt-4 text-sm font-black text-orange-900">{app.pricing}</p></a>)}</div>
  </section>

  <section class="border-y-2 rule bg-[#fff7ed] py-16">
    <div class="container grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[.8fr_1.2fr]">
      <div><span class="badge">Long-form editorial brief</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">How to choose email software without confusing automation with strategy.</h2></div>
      <div class="prose-shopify">
        <p>Most Shopify email pages look the same because they treat every platform as a template library with a few automations attached. Merchants need a sharper lens. Email is the channel where the store explains itself after a visitor leaves: why the product matters, how to choose the right variant, what happens after purchase, when the item should be replenished, which customers deserve early access, and when a shopper should be left alone.</p>
        <p>The best {site.keywordPlural} should therefore be evaluated around lifecycle clarity. Can the app build a welcome series that changes when someone buys? Can abandoned cart email reference the product and the hesitation rather than simply waving a coupon? Can post-purchase messages reduce support tickets? Can replenishment timing respect category differences? Can winback email identify a valuable lapsed customer without harassing everyone who has ever ordered?</p>
        <p>This rebuild gives the email site an editorial magazine identity: warmer colors, print-like cards, and copy that talks about inbox trust. The point is to make the domain feel distinct from the broader marketing-app site. Here, every recommendation is filtered through the email program a Shopify operator actually has to maintain: deliverability, consent, segmentation, creative cadence, customer respect, and revenue that survives beyond the attribution window.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-16"><div class="mb-8"><span class="badge">Flow library</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Email use cases by lifecycle moment</h2></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4">{USE_CASES.slice(0,12).map(u=><a class="card" href={`/use-cases/${u.slug}`}><h3 class="text-xl font-black text-stone-950">{u.name}</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-stone-700">Use email to {u.job}, while protecting inbox trust and margin.</p></a>)}</div></section>
  <section class="container pb-16"><div class="mb-8"><span class="badge">Industry notes</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Email strategy changes by catalog and buying cycle</h2></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{SEGMENTS.map(s=><a class="card" href={`/for/${s.slug}`}><h3 class="text-xl font-black text-stone-950">{s.name}</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-stone-700">Plan email around {s.pain}; the cadence should match the way customers actually decide.</p></a>)}</div></section>
  <section class="border-y-2 rule bg-[#fff7ed] py-16">
    <div class="container grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[.8fr_1.2fr]">
      <div><span class="badge">Homepage deep brief</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">A longer Shopify email marketing framework for the whole site</h2></div>
      <article class="prose-shopify">
        <p>Choosing among {site.keywordPlural} should start with the inbox experience a customer will actually receive. A Shopify merchant should subscribe, browse, abandon, purchase, wait, reorder, and lapse through the store like a real shopper. The audit usually reveals the same problems: a welcome series that never changes after purchase, cart recovery that discounts too quickly, product education that arrives after the support ticket, replenishment reminders that ignore category timing, and campaign calendars that speak to every subscriber as if they have the same relationship with the brand.</p>
        <p>The homepage is the map for fixing those problems. App reviews explain platform fit. Comparison pages show tradeoffs between two choices. Use-case pages turn one lifecycle job into a flow structure. Store-type guides translate the advice into catalog reality, because a beauty subscription brand, a jewelry gift store, a fashion drop business, and a high-AOV home goods shop do not need the same cadence. The right software is the one that makes those distinctions easy to maintain after the launch excitement fades.</p>
        <p>Strong email programs also need restraint. More messages can create more attributed revenue while weakening the list, training shoppers to wait, and hiding margin damage. That is why this site emphasizes consent, segmentation, suppression, deliverability, offer policy, mobile creative, and revenue quality. A good app should help the team send messages customers understand: why now, why this product, why this offer, and what happens next. If a platform cannot answer those questions with Shopify data, it may be a sender rather than a retention system.</p>
        <p>Use the ranked shortlist as a starting point, then read deeper by intent. If the store is migrating from a legacy tool, start with alternatives and comparisons. If the store is building flows for the first time, start with welcome, abandoned cart, post-purchase, replenishment, and winback. If category fit is the question, start with the store-type guides. The goal is not to collect every possible feature; it is to build a weekly operating rhythm where one flow improves, one campaign supports merchandising, and every send earns its place in the customer's inbox.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="container py-16">
    <div class="mb-8 max-w-4xl"><span class="badge">Practical evaluation rubric</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Score an email app by the work it prevents, not the features it advertises.</h2><p class="mt-4 text-stone-700">A good shortlist should survive a working session with a real Shopify store. Give each candidate a score from 1 to 5 in the areas below, then write down the evidence. The exercise is intentionally concrete: if the team cannot prove the answer inside the product, the score should be low even if the sales page says the feature exists.</p></div>
    <div class="grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
      <div class="card"><h3 class="text-xl font-black text-stone-950">Shopify data depth</h3><p class="mt-3 text-sm text-stone-700">Can marketers build segments from product viewed, SKU purchased, collection interest, order count, discount used, refund history, subscription status, customer tags, and consent source without CSV exports?</p></div>
      <div class="card"><h3 class="text-xl font-black text-stone-950">Lifecycle builder quality</h3><p class="mt-3 text-sm text-stone-700">Can the app create welcome, cart, browse, post-purchase, replenishment, winback, VIP, and launch flows with exclusions that prevent buyers from receiving contradictory messages?</p></div>
      <div class="card"><h3 class="text-xl font-black text-stone-950">Deliverability discipline</h3><p class="mt-3 text-sm text-stone-700">Does the platform make list health visible through complaints, bounces, engagement decay, sunset segments, preference capture, and send-volume warnings?</p></div>
      <div class="card"><h3 class="text-xl font-black text-stone-950">Creative operations</h3><p class="mt-3 text-sm text-stone-700">Can a lean team reuse product blocks, preserve mobile readability, localize offers, test subject lines, and QA links without rebuilding every campaign from scratch?</p></div>
      <div class="card"><h3 class="text-xl font-black text-stone-950">Revenue quality</h3><p class="mt-3 text-sm text-stone-700">Does reporting separate flow revenue from campaign revenue, show revenue per recipient, expose discount cost, and help decide whether a campaign created incremental behavior?</p></div>
      <div class="card"><h3 class="text-xl font-black text-stone-950">Operating burden</h3><p class="mt-3 text-sm text-stone-700">How many manual steps are required every week to build segments, suppress recent buyers, import creative, approve a campaign, and document what changed?</p></div>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="border-y-2 rule bg-[#fff7ed] py-16">
    <div class="container grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[.85fr_1.15fr]">
      <div><span class="badge">Implementation newsroom</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">A 30-day email launch plan for Shopify operators</h2><p class="mt-4 text-stone-700">Use this sequence when installing a new platform or trying to repair a shallow program. It gives the team enough structure to launch quickly without copying every old mistake into a cleaner editor.</p></div>
      <article class="prose-shopify">
        <h3>Week 1: consent, capture, and the first promise</h3><p>Audit every signup form, popup, checkout consent source, discount code, and preference center. The welcome email should reflect the promise that caused the signup. A shopper who joined for a first-order offer needs a different first message than a shopper who joined a launch waitlist or a replenishment reminder. Confirm that consent is synced to Shopify, that unsubscribes travel both directions, and that the platform can identify customers who should not receive promotional mail.</p>
        <h3>Week 2: conversion flows with exclusions</h3><p>Build or rebuild welcome, abandoned cart, and browse abandonment. Do not start with ten messages. Start with two or three that answer the hesitation: product fit, shipping, returns, ingredients, sizing, reviews, financing, or urgency. Add hard exclusions for recent buyers, support escalations, and customers already in a stronger flow. Then open ten customer timelines manually and verify that the emails arrived in a sensible order.</p>
        <h3>Week 3: post-purchase and second-order work</h3><p>The first order is not the finish line. Add delivery reassurance, usage education, care instructions, review capture, cross-sell, replenishment, or subscription education depending on the catalog. The best email marketing apps make product-specific branching manageable, so a skincare routine, a pet food reorder, and a jewelry gift follow-up do not all receive the same generic thank-you sequence.</p>
        <h3>Week 4: measurement and the next campaign calendar</h3><p>Compare platform attribution with Shopify orders, then inspect margin after discounts, revenue per recipient, unsubscribe pressure, complaint rate, repeat purchase, and support outcomes. Write the next month of campaigns around merchandising moments: a launch, a collection refresh, a replenishment cohort, a VIP preview, a back-in-stock drop, or a seasonal buying guide. If a campaign cannot explain its audience, offer, landing page, suppression, and success metric, hold it back.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* HERMES_HOME_DEEP_PASS_JULY5 */}
  <section class="container pb-16">
    <article class="prose-shopify card">
      <h2>How this email marketing operator desk separates serious tools from thin directories</h2>
      <p>The homepage is meant to be a working buyer map, not a listicle with swapped logos. Every recommendation starts from the same question: can a Shopify merchant use the tool to improve forms, welcome, cart, browse, post-purchase, product launches, VIP segments, deliverability, and lifecycle reporting without creating more weekly cleanup? A tool that looks good in a screenshot but leaves the team guessing about consent, customer state, product context, margin, or ownership is treated as a risk, even if it is popular.</p>
      <p>The scoring favors operational evidence. A email marketer should be able to name the first workflow to launch, the audience that deserves it, the customers to suppress, the product fields that change the message, the metric that proves quality, and the person who will review it next week. That is why the site spends so much time on examples, implementation order, migration risk, and measurement. Those are the details that separate a useful email marketing app from another app subscription.</p>
      <p>The biggest failure mode is migrating templates while leaving segmentation, suppression, and attribution shallow. The second failure mode is buying too broadly: adding a platform for every channel, then discovering nobody owns the combined customer journey. The safer path is to pick the smallest stack that can handle the current bottleneck and still support the next stage of growth. For some stores that means Sequenzy as a lean lifecycle layer. For others it means a mature platform with deeper data controls. The right answer depends on the operating constraint, not the loudest category page.</p>
      <p>Use the site like a due-diligence checklist. Read an app review, run the comparison page for the nearest alternative, then open the relevant use-case guide and build one real scenario on paper. If the tool cannot pass that scenario, the ranking should not matter. If it passes and the economics work against flow revenue quality, repeat purchase movement, deliverability, margin after offers, unsubscribe pressure, and campaign learning speed, it belongs on the shortlist.</p>
    </article>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
